(1083, 8, 'Watch: The Bible Interprets the Bible', 'video', '<p>Now watch this <strong>~15&nbsp;minute</strong> teaching segment on <strong>The Bible Interprets the Bible</strong>. Have your notes from the two readings beside you.</p>\n<p>As you watch, listen for: (1) anything that confirms what you read, (2) anything new, and (3) one question it raises. Add these to your lesson notes, then mark the lesson complete.</p>', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=plSNIwhAn5o&start=0&end=900', 15, 63, NULL, 7, 'The Bible Interprets the Bible'),
(1084, 8, 'Read: From Meaning to Significance', 'reading', '<p style="color:#6b6b60"><em>Estimated reading time: 7–10 minutes.</em></p>\n<h3>Why this matters</h3>\n<p>Hermeneutics is the discipline of interpreting Scripture well — reading each text according to its genre, context and place in the biblical story.</p>\n<p>In this lesson we focus on <strong>From Meaning to Significance</strong>, one of the foundational topics within biblical interpretation. Getting it right shapes how you read Scripture, how you pray and worship, and how you serve and lead others. Read this slowly — perhaps twice — with a Bible and a notebook beside you. The goal is not simply to gather information for an assignment, but to let the truth take root and change you. As the apostle Paul writes, we are transformed by the renewing of our minds, and that renewal begins with careful, prayerful attention.</p>\n<p>Before you read on, pause for a moment of prayer. Ask God to open your understanding and to make this lesson more than an academic exercise. The best theology is always done on our knees as well as at our desks.</p>\n<h3>Getting our bearings</h3>\n<p>Whenever we approach a topic like <strong>From Meaning to Significance</strong>, it helps to slow down and ask what we actually mean by the words we are using. Christians sometimes assume everyone shares the same definitions, and a great deal of confusion comes from skipping this step. So take a moment to write down, in your own words, what you already think about from meaning to significance. Where did that understanding come from — a sermon, a book, your family, your culture? Naming our starting point honestly is the first act of good learning, because it lets us hold our assumptions up to the light of Scripture rather than reading our assumptions into Scripture.</p>\n<p>You will notice that the Bible rarely hands us a tidy, dictionary-style definition. Instead it tells a story and invites us to live inside it. From Meaning to Significan