g> change the way I pray this week, the way I treat the people around me, and the way I lead or serve in my church and community? Choose one concrete, specific response — not a vague intention — and write it down. Good learning ends in worship and obedience, not merely in notes; the test of this lesson is not the quiz but your life.</p>\n<h3>Summary</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Common Interpretive Mistakes is rooted in Scripture and must be tested against the whole biblical story, not one isolated verse.</li>\n<li>We read it with the historic and global church, holding conviction together with humility and charity.</li>\n<li>True understanding joins head and heart — text, confession and love.</li>\n<li>The aim is transformation: worship, character and faithful service, not information alone.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Reflect</h3>\n<p>Write two or three sentences explaining Common Interpretive Mistakes in your own words, as if to a friend who is new to faith. Then note one question you still have. Bring both to the supporting study, the video, and your cohort discussion.</p>', NULL, 9, 81, NULL, 9, 'Common Interpretive Mistakes'),
(1088, 8, 'Study: Common Interpretive Mistakes', 'reading', '<p style="color:#6b6b60"><em>Estimated reading time: 5–7 minutes.</em></p>\n<h3>A closer look: Common Interpretive Mistakes</h3>\n<p>The main reading gave you the big picture. This shorter reading helps you dig into the Bible for yourself, because the most important skill you can develop is reading Scripture well and prayerfully.</p>\n<h3>Study these passages</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Read <a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=2%20Timothy%202%3A15&version=NIVUK" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>2 Timothy 2:15</strong></a>. What does this passage show about common interpretive mistakes? Note one phrase that stands out.</li>\n<li>Read <a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Nehemiah%208%3A1-8&version=NIVUK" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Nehemiah 8:1-8</strong></a>. How does it deepen or balance the first passage?</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Questions for reflection &amp; discussion</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>In one sentence, how would you explain <strong>Common Interpretive Mistakes</strong> to someone in your church?</li>\n<li>Where do you see this lived out — well or poorly — in the world around you?</li>\n<li>What might God be inviting you to change in response?</li>\n<li>What question would you like to raise with your cohort?</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Going further</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Re-read both passages in a second translation and compare.</li>\n<li>Post your one-sentence explanation and your question in the discussion forum.</li>\n<li>Watch the video in the next lesson, then return and refine your answer.</li>\n</ul>', NULL, 6, 82, NULL, 9, 'Common Interpretive Mistakes'),
(1089, 8, 'Watch: Common Interpretive Mistakes', 'video', '<p>Now watch this <strong>~15&nbsp;minute</strong> teaching segment on <strong>Common Interpretive Mistakes</strong>. Have your notes from the two readings beside you.</p>\n<p>As you watch, listen for: (1) anything that confirms what you read, (2) anything new, and (3) one question it raises. Add these to your lesson notes, then mark the lesson complete.</p>', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GK2PBAG3064&start=0&end=900', 15, 83, NULL, 9, 'Common Interpretive Mistakes'),
(1090, 8, 'Read: A Method for Faithful Reading', 'reading', '<p style="color:#6b6b60"><em>Estimated reading time: 7–10 minutes.</em></p>\n<h3>Why this matters</h3>\n<p>Hermeneutics is the discipline of interpreting Scripture well — reading each text according to its genre, context and place in the biblical story.</p>\n<p>In this lesson we focus on <strong>A Method for Faithful Reading</strong>, one of the foundational topics within biblical interpretation. Getting it right shapes how you read Scripture, how you pray and worship, and how you serve and lead others. Read this slowly — perhaps twice — with a Bible and a notebook beside you. The goal is not simply to gather information for an assignment, but to let the truth take root and change you. As the apostle Paul writes, we are transformed by the renewing of our minds, and that renewal begins with careful, prayerful attention.</p>\n<p>Before you read on, pause for a moment of prayer. Ask God to open your understanding and to make this lesson more than an academic exercise. The best theology is always done on our knees as well as at our desks.</p>\n<h3>Getting our bearings</h3>\n<p>Whenever we approach a topic like <strong>A Method for Faithful Reading</strong>, it helps to slow down and ask what we actually mean by the words we are using. Christians sometimes assume everyone shares the same definitions, and a great deal of confusion comes from skipping this step. So take a moment to write down, in your own words, what you already think about a method for faithful reading. Where did that understanding come from — a sermon, a book, your family, your culture? Naming our starting point honestly is the first act of good learning, because it lets us hold our assumptions up to the light of Scripture rather than reading our assumptions into Scripture.</p>\n<p>You will notice that the Bible rarely hands us a tidy, dictionary-style definition. Instead it tells a story and invites us to live inside it. A Method for Faithful Reading is therefore best understood not as an abstract idea to be filed away, but as a thread woven through the whole drama of Scripture — a drama that finds its centre and fulfilment in Jesus Christ.</p>\n<h3>What Scripture says</h3>\n<p>Begin with the Bible itself. Read <a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Nehemiah%208%3A1-8&version=NIVUK" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Nehemiah 8:1-8</strong></a> before going further; do not rush past it. Scripture is our first and final authority, and every Christian conviction about a method for faithful reading must be tested against it rather than against our preferences or traditions.</p>\n<p>As you read, ask three questions. First, what did this text mean for its original hearers, in their language, culture and moment? Second, how does it fit within the Bible’s one unfolding story of creation, fall, redemption and new creation? Third, what does it reveal about the character and purposes of God? These three questions — the historical, the canonical and the theological — keep us from twisting a verse to say whatever we want. Write down at least one observation under each question before moving on.</p>\n<h3>Across the Bible’s story</h3>\n<p>No single passage stands alone. A Method for Faithful Reading appears, in different forms, from the opening chapters of Genesis through to the closing vision of Revelation. The same God who acts at creation is at work through Israel, supremely in Jesus, and now through his church by the Spirit. Tracing a theme across these movements guards us against building a whole doctrine on one isolated text, and it lets the clearer parts of Scripture illuminate the harder ones. As you study this year, keep asking: where else does the Bible touch on this, and how does the story as a whole shape what I am reading here?</p>\n<h3>How the church has understood it</h3>\n<p>Christians have reflected on a method for faithful reading for two thousand years, and we are wise to learn from them rather than starting from scratch. The early church, the great councils, the Reformers, and theologians of the modern and global church have all wrestled with these questions and left us hard-won wisdom. Tradition is not a second authority standing above Scripture; it is a trustworthy companion — a long conversation of faithful readers that helps us avoid old errors and see what we might miss on our own.</p>\n<p>Where sincere Christians have disagreed, make it your habit to understand the strongest form of each view before you settle your own. Charity and humility are not weaknesses in a theologian; they are marks of maturity, and they protect both truth and unity.</p>\n<h3>A common misunderstanding</h3>\n<p>It is worth naming a frequent mistake here. Many people reduce a method for faithful reading either to dry information that makes no difference to daily life, or to a private feeling disconnected from the teaching of Scripture. Both extremes fail. Genuine Christian understanding joins head and heart: it is rooted in the text, confessed with the church, and lived out in love. If your study of A Method for Faithful Reading leaves you more proud, more anxious, or more detached from people, something has gone wrong in the method, however correct the conclusions.</p>\n<h3>In the global and diaspora church</h3>\n<p>GDCU exists for a worldwide, diaspora community, so we always ask how a topic lands across cultures. A Method for Faithful Reading is often understood more richly when read through the eyes of the global church in Africa, Asia, Latin America and among scattered and migrant peoples. Your own context is not a problem to overcome but a gift that helps the whole body of Christ see more of the truth. As you read, consider how this topic speaks into your own community, its questions, its sufferings and its hopes.</p>\n<h3>For your life and ministry</h3>\n<p>Theology is meant to be lived. Ask yourself honestly: how should <strong>A Method for Faithful Reading</strong> change the way I pray this week, the way I treat the people around me, and the way I lead or serve in my church and community? Choose one concrete, specific response — not a vague intention — and write it down. Good learning ends in worship and obedience, not merely in notes; the test of this lesson is not the quiz but your life.</p>\n<h3>Summary</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>A Method for Faithful Reading is rooted in Scripture and must be tested against the whole biblical story, not one isolated verse.</li>\n<li>We read it with the historic and global church, holding conviction together with humility and charity.</li>\n<li>True understanding joins head and heart — text, confession and love.</li>\n<li>The aim is transformation: worship, character and faithful service, not information alone.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Reflect</h3>\n<p>Write two or three sentences explaining A Method for Faithful Reading in your own words, as if to a friend who is new to faith. Then note one question you still have. Bring both to the supporting study, the video, and your cohort discussion.</p>', NULL, 9, 91, NULL, 10, 'A Method for Faithful Reading'),
(1091, 8, 'Study: A Method for Faithful Reading', 'reading', '<p style="color:#6b6b60"><em>Estimated reading time: 5–7 minutes.</em></p>\n<h3>A closer look: A Method for Faithful Reading</h3>\n<p>The main reading gave you the big picture. This shorter reading helps you dig into the Bible for yourself, because the most important skill you can develop is reading Scripture well and prayerfully.</p>\n<h3>Study these passages</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Read <a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Nehemiah%208%3A1-8&version=NIVUK" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Nehemiah 8:1-8</strong></a>. What does this passage show about a method for faithful reading? Note one phrase that stands out.</li>\n<li>Read <a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Acts%208%3A26-35&version=NIVUK" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Acts 8:26-35</strong></a>. How does it deepen or balance the first passage?</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Questions for reflection &amp; discussion</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>In one sentence, how would you explain <strong>A Method for Faithful Reading</strong> to someone in your church?</li>\n<li>Where do you see this lived out — well or poorly — in the world around you?</li>\n<li>What might God be inviting you to change in response?</li>\n<li>What question would you like to raise with your cohort?</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Going further</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Re-read both passages in a second translation and compare.</li>\n<li>Post your one-sentence explanation and your question in the discussion forum.</li>\n<li>Watch the video in the next lesson, then return and refine your answer.</li>\n</ul>', NULL, 6, 92, NULL, 10, 'A Method for Faithful Reading'),
(1092, 8, 'Watch: A Method for Faithful Reading', 'video', '<p>Now watch this <strong>~15&nbsp;minute</strong> teaching segment on <strong>A Method for Faithful Reading</strong>. Have your notes from the two readings beside you.</p>\n<p>As you watch, listen for: (1) anything that confirms what you read, (2) anything new, and (3) one question it raises. Add these to your lesson notes, then mark the lesson complete.</p>', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GK2PBAG3064&start=900&end=1800', 15, 93, NULL, 10, 'A Method for Faithful Reading'),
(1093, 9, 'Read: The Apostolic Church', 'reading', '<p style="color:#6b6b60"><em>Estimated reading time: 7–10 minutes.</em></p>\n<h3>Why this matters</h3>\n<p>From Pentecost to the Reformation the church spread across the world, confessed Christ in the creeds, and weathered persecution, councils and renewal.</p>\n<p>In this lesson we focus on <strong>The Apostolic Church</strong>, one of the foundational topics within the early church. Getting it right shapes how you read Scripture, how you pray and worship, and how you serve and lead others. Read this slowly — perhaps twice — with a Bible and a notebook beside you. The goal is not simply to gather information for an assignment, but to let the truth take root and change you. As the apostle Paul writes, we are transformed by the renewing of our minds, and that renewal begins with careful, prayerful attention.</p>\n<p>Before you read on, pause for a moment of prayer. Ask God to open your understanding and to make this lesson more than an academic exercise. The best theology is always done on our knees as well as at our desks.</p>\n<h3>Getting our bearings</h3>\n<p>Whenever we approach a topic like <strong>The Apostolic Church</strong>, it helps to slow down and ask what we actually mean by the words we are using. Christians sometimes assume everyone shares the same definitions, and a great deal of confusion comes from skipping this step. So take a moment to write down, in your own words, what you already think about the apostolic church. Where did that understanding come from — a sermon, a book, your family, your culture? Naming our starting point honestly is the first act of good learning, because it lets us hold our assumptions up to the light of Scripture rather than reading our assumptions into Scripture.</p>\n<p>You will notice that the Bible rarely hands us a tidy, dictionary-style definition. Instead it tells a story and invites us to live inside it. The Apostolic Church is therefore best understood not as an abstract idea to be filed away, but as a thread woven through the whole drama of Scripture — a drama that finds its centre and fulfilment in Jesus Christ.</p>\n<h3>What Scripture says</h3>\n<p>Begin with the Bible itself. Read <a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Acts%202%3A42-47&version=NIVUK" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Acts 2:42-47</strong></a> before going further; do not rush past it. Scripture is our first and final authority, and every Christian conviction about the apostolic church must be tested against it rather than against our preferences or traditions.</p>\n<p>As you read, ask three questions. First, what did this text mean for its original hearers, in their language, culture and moment? Second, how does it fit within the Bible’s one unfolding story of creation, fall, redemption and new creation? Third, what does it reveal about the character and purposes of God? These three questions — the historical, the canonical and the theological — keep us from twisting a verse to say whatever we want. Write down at least one observation under each question before moving on.</p>\n<h3>Across the Bible’s story</h3>\n<p>No single passage stands alone. The Apostolic Church appears, in different forms, from the opening chapters of Genesis through to the closing vision of Revelation. The same God who acts at creation is at work through Israel, supremely in Jesus, and now through his church by the Spirit. Tracing a theme across these movements guards us against building a whole doctrine on one isolated text, and it lets the clearer parts of Scripture illuminate the harder ones. As you study this year, keep asking: where else does the Bible touch on this, and how does the story as a whole shape what I am reading here?</p>\n<h3>How the church has understood it</h3>\n<p>Christians have reflected on the apostolic church for two thousand years, and we are wise to learn from them rather than starting from scratch. The early church, the great councils, the Reformers, and theologians of the modern and global church have all wrestled with these questions and left us hard-won wisdom. Tradition is not a second authority standing above Scripture; it is a trustworthy companion — a long conversation of faithful readers that helps us avoid old errors and see what we might miss on our own.</p>\n<p>Where sincere Christians have disagreed, make it your habit to understand the strongest form of each view before you settle your own. Charity and humility are not weaknesses in a theologian; they are marks of maturity, and they protect both truth and unity.</p>\n<h3>A common misunderstanding</h3>\n<p>It is worth naming a frequent mistake here. Many people reduce the apostolic church either to dry information that makes no difference to daily life, or to a private feeling disconnected from the teaching of Scripture. Both extremes fail. Genuine Christian understanding joins head and heart: it is rooted in the text, confessed with the church, and lived out in love. If your study of The Apostolic Church leaves you more proud, more anxious, or more detached from people, something has gone wrong in the method, however correct the conclusions.</p>\n<h3>In the global and diaspora church</h3>\n<p>GDCU exists for a worldwide, diaspora community, so we always ask how a topic lands across cultures. The Apostolic Church is often understood more richly when read through the eyes of the global church in Africa, Asia, Latin America and among scattered and migrant peoples. Your own context is not a problem to overcome but a gift that helps the whole body of Christ see more of the truth. As you read, consider how this topic speaks into your own community, its questions, its sufferings and its hopes.</p>\n<h3>For your life and ministry</h3>\n<p>Theology is meant to be lived. Ask yourself honestly: how should <strong>The Apostolic Church</strong> change the way I pray this week, the way I treat the people around me, and the way I lead or serve in my church and community? Choose one concrete, specific response — not a vague intention — and write it down. Good learning ends in worship and obedience, not merely in notes; the test of this lesson is not the quiz but your life.</p>\n<h3>Summary</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>The Apostolic Church is rooted in Scripture and must be tested against the whole biblical story, not one isolated verse.</li>\n<li>We read it with the historic and global church, holding conviction together with humility and charity.</li>\n<li>True understanding joins head and heart — text, confession and love.</li>\n<li>The aim is transformation: worship, character and faithful service, not information alone.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Reflect</h3>\n<p>Write two or three sentences explaining The Apostolic Church in your own words, as if to a friend who is new to faith. Then note one question you still have. Bring both to the supporting study, the video, and your cohort discussion.</p>', NULL, 9, 1, NULL, 1, 'The Apostolic Church');
