h, the great councils, the Reformers, and theologians of the modern and global church have all wrestled with these questions and left us hard-won wisdom. Tradition is not a second authority standing above Scripture; it is a trustworthy companion — a long conversation of faithful readers that helps us avoid old errors and see what we might miss on our own.</p>\n<p>Where sincere Christians have disagreed, make it your habit to understand the strongest form of each view before you settle your own. Charity and humility are not weaknesses in a theologian; they are marks of maturity, and they protect both truth and unity.</p>\n<h3>A common misunderstanding</h3>\n<p>It is worth naming a frequent mistake here. Many people reduce love of god & neighbour either to dry information that makes no difference to daily life, or to a private feeling disconnected from the teaching of Scripture. Both extremes fail. Genuine Christian understanding joins head and heart: it is rooted in the text, confessed with the church, and lived out in love. If your study of Love of God & Neighbour leaves you more proud, more anxious, or more detached from people, something has gone wrong in the method, however correct the conclusions.</p>\n<h3>In the global and diaspora church</h3>\n<p>GDCU exists for a worldwide, diaspora community, so we always ask how a topic lands across cultures. Love of God & Neighbour is often understood more richly when read through the eyes of the global church in Africa, Asia, Latin America and among scattered and migrant peoples. Your own context is not a problem to overcome but a gift that helps the whole body of Christ see more of the truth. As you read, consider how this topic speaks into your own community, its questions, its sufferings and its hopes.</p>\n<h3>For your life and ministry</h3>\n<p>Theology is meant to be lived. Ask yourself honestly: how should <strong>Love of God & Neighbour</strong> change the way I pray this week, the way I treat the people around me