(1297, 15, 'Read: Mission & Justice', 'reading', '<p style="color:#6b6b60"><em>Estimated reading time: 7–10 minutes.</em></p>\n<h3>Why this matters</h3>\n<p>Mission flows from the heart of God. The church is sent to make disciples of all nations, announcing and embodying the good news of the kingdom.</p>\n<p>In this lesson we focus on <strong>Mission & Justice</strong>, one of the foundational topics within mission and evangelism. Getting it right shapes how you read Scripture, how you pray and worship, and how you serve and lead others. Read this slowly — perhaps twice — with a Bible and a notebook beside you. The goal is not simply to gather information for an assignment, but to let the truth take root and change you. As the apostle Paul writes, we are transformed by the renewing of our minds, and that renewal begins with careful, prayerful attention.</p>\n<p>Before you read on, pause for a moment of prayer. Ask God to open your understanding and to make this lesson more than an academic exercise. The best theology is always done on our knees as well as at our desks.</p>\n<h3>Getting our bearings</h3>\n<p>Whenever we approach a topic like <strong>Mission & Justice</strong>, it helps to slow down and ask what we actually mean by the words we are using. Christians sometimes assume everyone shares the same definitions, and a great deal of confusion comes from skipping this step. So take a moment to write down, in your own words, what you already think about mission & justice. Where did that understanding come from — a sermon, a book, your family, your culture? Naming our starting point honestly is the first act of good learning, because it lets us hold our assumptions up to the light of Scripture rather than reading our assumptions into Scripture.</p>\n<p>You will notice that the Bible rarely hands us a tidy, dictionary-style definition. Instead it tells a story and invites us to live inside it. Mission & Justice is therefore best understood not as an abstract idea to be filed away, but as a thread woven through the whole drama of Scripture — a drama that finds its centre and fulfilment in Jesus Christ.</p>\n<h3>What Scripture says</h3>\n<p>Begin with the Bible itself. Read <a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Matthew%2028%3A16-20&version=NIVUK" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Matthew 28:16-20</strong></a> before going further; do not rush past it. Scripture is our first and final authority, and every Christian conviction about mission & justice must be tested against it rather than against our preferences or traditions.</p>\n<p>As you read, ask three questions. First, what did this text mean for its original hearers, in their language, culture and moment? Second, how does it fit within the Bible’s one unfolding story of creation, fall, redemption and new creation? Third, what does it reveal about the character and purposes of God? These three questions — the historical, the canonical and the theological — keep us from twisting a verse to say whatever we want. Write down at least one observation under each question before moving on.</p>\n<h3>Across the Bible’s story</h3>\n<p>No single passage stands alone. Mission & Justice appears, in different forms, from the opening chapters of Genesis through to the closing vision of Revelation. The same God who acts at creation is at work through Israel, supremely in Jesus, and now through his church by the Spirit. Tracing a theme across these movements guards us against building a whole doctrine on one isolated text, and it lets the clearer parts of Scripture illuminate the harder ones. As you study this year, keep asking: where else does the Bible touch on this, and how does the story as a whole shape what I am reading here?</p>\n<h3>How the church has understood it</h3>\n<p>Christians have reflected on mission & justice for two thousand years, and we are wise to learn from them rather than starting from scratch. The early church, the great councils, the Reformers, and theologians of the modern and global church have all wrestled with these questions and left us hard-won wisdom. Tradition is not a second authority standing above Scripture; it is a trustworthy companion — a long conversation of faithful readers that helps us avoid old errors and see what we might miss on our own.</p>\n<p>Where sincere Christians have disagreed, make it your habit to understand the strongest form of each view before you settle your own. Charity and humility are not weaknesses in a theologian; they are marks of maturity, and they protect both truth and unity.</p>\n<h3>A common misunderstanding</h3>\n<p>It is worth naming a frequent mistake here. Many people reduce mission & justice either to dry information that makes no difference to daily life, or to a private feeling disconnected from the teaching of Scripture. Both extremes fail. Genuine Christian understanding joins head and heart: it is rooted in the text, confessed with the church, and lived out in love. If your study of Mission & Justice leaves you more proud, more anxious, or more detached from people, something has gone wrong in the method, however correct the conclusions.</p>\n<h3>In the global and diaspora church</h3>\n<p>GDCU exists for a worldwide, diaspora community, so we always ask how a topic lands across cultures. Mission & Justice is often understood more richly when read through the eyes of the global church in Africa, Asia, Latin America and among scattered and migrant peoples. Your own context is not a problem to overcome but a gift that helps the whole body of Christ see more of the truth. As you read, consider how this topic speaks into your own community, its questions, its sufferings and its hopes.</p>\n<h3>For your life and ministry</h3>\n<p>Theology is meant to be lived. Ask yourself honestly: how should <strong>Mission & Justice</strong> change the way I pray this week, the way I treat the people around me, and the way I lead or serve in my church and community? Choose one concrete, specific response — not a vague intention — and write it down. Good learning ends in worship and obedience, not merely in notes; the test of this lesson is not the quiz but your life.</p>\n<h3>Summary</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Mission & Justice is rooted in Scripture and must be tested against the whole biblical story, not one isolated verse.</li>\n<li>We read it with the historic and global church, holding conviction together with humility and charity.</li>\n<li>True understanding joins head and heart — text, confession and love.</li>\n<li>The aim is transformation: worship, character and faithful service, not information alone.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Reflect</h3>\n<p>Write two or three sentences explaining Mission & Justice in your own words, as if to a friend who is new to faith. Then note one question you still have. Bring both to the supporting study, the video, and your cohort discussion.</p>', NULL, 9, 81, NULL, 9, 'Mission & Justice'),
(1298, 15, 'Study: Mission & Justice', 'reading', '<p style="color:#6b6b60"><em>Estimated reading time: 5–7 minutes.</em></p>\n<h3>A closer look: Mission & Justice</h3>\n<p>The main reading gave you the big picture. This shorter reading helps you dig into the Bible for yourself, because the most important skill you can develop is reading Scripture well and prayerfully.</p>\n<h3>Study these passages</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Read <a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Matthew%2028%3A16-20&version=NIVUK" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Matthew 28:16-20</strong></a>. What does this passage show about mission & justice? Note one phrase that stands out.</li>\n<li>Read <a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Luke%204%3A16-21&version=NIVUK" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Luke 4:16-21</strong></a>. How does it deepen or balance the first passage?</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Questions for reflection &amp; discussion</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>In one sentence, how would you explain <strong>Mission & Justice</strong> to someone in your church?</li>\n<li>Where do you see this lived out — well or poorly — in the world around you?</li>\n<li>What might God be inviting you to change in response?</li>\n<li>What question would you like to raise with your cohort?</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Going further</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Re-read both passages in a second translation and compare.</li>\n<li>Post your one-sentence explanation and your question in the discussion forum.</li>\n<li>Watch the video in the next lesson, then return and refine your answer.</li>\n</ul>', NULL, 6, 82, NULL, 9, 'Mission & Justice'),
(1299, 15, 'Watch: Mission & Justice', 'video', '<p>Now watch this <strong>~15&nbsp;minute</strong> teaching segment on <strong>Mission & Justice</strong>. Have your notes from the two readings beside you.</p>\n<p>As you watch, listen for: (1) anything that confirms what you read, (2) anything new, and (3) one question it raises. Add these to your lesson notes, then mark the lesson complete.</p>', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=GGCF3OPWN14&start=0&end=900', 15, 83, NULL, 9, 'Mission & Justice'),
(1300, 15, 'Read: Everyday Witness', 'reading', '<p style="color:#6b6b60"><em>Estimated reading time: 7–10 minutes.</em></p>\n<h3>Why this matters</h3>\n<p>Mission flows from the heart of God. The church is sent to make disciples of all nations, announcing and embodying the good news of the kingdom.</p>\n<p>In this lesson we focus on <strong>Everyday Witness</strong>, one of the foundational topics within mission and evangelism. Getting it right shapes how you read Scripture, how you pray and worship, and how you serve and lead others. Read this slowly — perhaps twice — with a Bible and a notebook beside you. The goal is not simply to gather information for an assignment, but to let the truth take root and change you. As the apostle Paul writes, we are transformed by the renewing of our minds, and that renewal begins with careful, prayerful attention.</p>\n<p>Before you read on, pause for a moment of prayer. Ask God to open your understanding and to make this lesson more than an academic exercise. The best theology is always done on our knees as well as at our desks.</p>\n<h3>Getting our bearings</h3>\n<p>Whenever we approach a topic like <strong>Everyday Witness</strong>, it helps to slow down and ask what we actually mean by the words we are using. Christians sometimes assume everyone shares the same definitions, and a great deal of confusion comes from skipping this step. So take a moment to write down, in your own words, what you already think about everyday witness. Where did that understanding come from — a sermon, a book, your family, your culture? Naming our starting point honestly is the first act of good learning, because it lets us hold our assumptions up to the light of Scripture rather than reading our assumptions into Scripture.</p>\n<p>You will notice that the Bible rarely hands us a tidy, dictionary-style definition. Instead it tells a story and invites us to live inside it. Everyday Witness is therefore best understood not as an abstract idea to be filed away, but as a thread woven through the whole drama of Scripture — a drama that finds its centre and fulfilment in Jesus Christ.</p>\n<h3>What Scripture says</h3>\n<p>Begin with the Bible itself. Read <a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Luke%204%3A16-21&version=NIVUK" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Luke 4:16-21</strong></a> before going further; do not rush past it. Scripture is our first and final authority, and every Christian conviction about everyday witness must be tested against it rather than against our preferences or traditions.</p>\n<p>As you read, ask three questions. First, what did this text mean for its original hearers, in their language, culture and moment? Second, how does it fit within the Bible’s one unfolding story of creation, fall, redemption and new creation? Third, what does it reveal about the character and purposes of God? These three questions — the historical, the canonical and the theological — keep us from twisting a verse to say whatever we want. Write down at least one observation under each question before moving on.</p>\n<h3>Across the Bible’s story</h3>\n<p>No single passage stands alone. Everyday Witness appears, in different forms, from the opening chapters of Genesis through to the closing vision of Revelation. The same God who acts at creation is at work through Israel, supremely in Jesus, and now through his church by the Spirit. Tracing a theme across these movements guards us against building a whole doctrine on one isolated text, and it lets the clearer parts of Scripture illuminate the harder ones. As you study this year, keep asking: where else does the Bible touch on this, and how does the story as a whole shape what I am reading here?</p>\n<h3>How the church has understood it</h3>\n<p>Christians have reflected on everyday witness for two thousand years, and we are wise to learn from them rather than starting from scratch. The early church, the great councils, the Reformers, and theologians of the modern and global church have all wrestled with these questions and left us hard-won wisdom. Tradition is not a second authority standing above Scripture; it is a trustworthy companion — a long conversation of faithful readers that helps us avoid old errors and see what we might miss on our own.</p>\n<p>Where sincere Christians have disagreed, make it your habit to understand the strongest form of each view before you settle your own. Charity and humility are not weaknesses in a theologian; they are marks of maturity, and they protect both truth and unity.</p>\n<h3>A common misunderstanding</h3>\n<p>It is worth naming a frequent mistake here. Many people reduce everyday witness either to dry information that makes no difference to daily life, or to a private feeling disconnected from the teaching of Scripture. Both extremes fail. Genuine Christian understanding joins head and heart: it is rooted in the text, confessed with the church, and lived out in love. If your study of Everyday Witness leaves you more proud, more anxious, or more detached from people, something has gone wrong in the method, however correct the conclusions.</p>\n<h3>In the global and diaspora church</h3>\n<p>GDCU exists for a worldwide, diaspora community, so we always ask how a topic lands across cultures. Everyday Witness is often understood more richly when read through the eyes of the global church in Africa, Asia, Latin America and among scattered and migrant peoples. Your own context is not a problem to overcome but a gift that helps the whole body of Christ see more of the truth. As you read, consider how this topic speaks into your own community, its questions, its sufferings and its hopes.</p>\n<h3>For your life and ministry</h3>\n<p>Theology is meant to be lived. Ask yourself honestly: how should <strong>Everyday Witness</strong> change the way I pray this week, the way I treat the people around me, and the way I lead or serve in my church and community? Choose one concrete, specific response — not a vague intention — and write it down. Good learning ends in worship and obedience, not merely in notes; the test of this lesson is not the quiz but your life.</p>\n<h3>Summary</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Everyday Witness is rooted in Scripture and must be tested against the whole biblical story, not one isolated verse.</li>\n<li>We read it with the historic and global church, holding conviction together with humility and charity.</li>\n<li>True understanding joins head and heart — text, confession and love.</li>\n<li>The aim is transformation: worship, character and faithful service, not information alone.</li>\n</ul>\n<h3>Reflect</h3>\n<p>Write two or three sentences explaining Everyday Witness in your own words, as if to a friend who is new to faith. Then note one question you still have. Bring both to the supporting study, the video, and your cohort discussion.</p>', NULL, 9, 91, NULL, 10, 'Everyday Witness'),
(1301, 15, 'Study: Everyday Witness', 'reading', '<p style="color:#6b6b60"><em>Estimated reading time: 5–7 minutes.</em></p>\n<h3>A closer look: Everyday Witness</h3>\n<p>The main reading gave you the big picture. This shorter reading helps you dig into the Bible for yourself, because the most important skill you can develop is reading Scripture well and prayerfully.</p>\n<h3>Study these passages</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>Read <a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Luke%204%3A16-21&version=NIVUK" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Luke 4:16-21</strong></a>. What does this passage show about everyday witness? Note one phrase that stands out.</li>\n<li>Read <a href="https://www.biblegateway.com/passage/?search=Acts%201%3A8&version=NIVUK" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><strong>Acts 1:8</strong></a>. How does it deepen or balance the first passage?</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Questions for reflection &amp; discussion</h3>\n<ol>\n<li>In one sentence, how would you explain <strong>Everyday Witness</strong> to someone in your church?</li>\n<li>Where do you see this lived out — well or poorly — in the world around you?</li>\n<li>What might God be inviting you to change in response?</li>\n<li>What question would you like to raise with your cohort?</li>\n</ol>\n<h3>Going further</h3>\n<ul>\n<li>Re-read both passages in a second translation and compare.</li>\n<li>Post your one-sentence explanation and your question in the discussion forum.</li>\n<li>Watch the video in the next lesson, then return and refine your answer.</li>\n</ul>', NULL, 6, 92, NULL, 10, 'Everyday Witness'),
(1302, 15, 'Watch: Everyday Witness', 'video', '<p>Now watch this <strong>~15&nbsp;minute</strong> teaching segment on <strong>Everyday Witness</strong>. Have your notes from the two readings beside you.</p>\n<p>As you watch, listen for: (1) anything that confirms what you read, (2) anything new, and (3) one question it raises. Add these to your lesson notes, then mark the lesson complete.</p>', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=f7RJATbobik&start=0&end=900', 15, 93, NULL, 10, 'Everyday Witness'),
(1398, 66, 'The Call to Faithful Enterprise', 'reading', '<p>Work is not a curse — it is part of God\'s original creation mandate. Explore how business, trade and enterprise are dignified callings in Scripture. From the Garden of Eden to the marketplace, God calls His people to create, steward and trade for the common good. This session reframes business as a form of worship and service.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 30, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1399, 66, 'Stewardship, Profit & Purpose', 'reading', '<p>Profit is not inherently ungodly. Scripture affirms the creation of value, fair exchange and wealth generation — but always within the bounds of justice, generosity and accountability. We examine the tension between maximising shareholder value and serving the common good, and how a Christian worldview resolves it through the principle of faithful stewardship.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 30, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1400, 66, 'Business as Mission: The Diaspora Advantage', 'reading', '<p>Diaspora communities are uniquely positioned to serve as bridges between economies, cultures and faith traditions. This lesson explores how global migration creates entrepreneurial opportunities for kingdom impact. Case studies of diaspora entrepreneurs who are transforming their communities through faith-driven businesses.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 30, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1401, 66, 'Integrating Faith & Strategy', 'reading', '<p>How do you actually integrate faith into strategic decisions? This practical session provides a framework for prayerful, principle-driven strategic thinking. We cover decision-making models that honour both Scripture and sound business logic, with worked examples from real business scenarios.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 35, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1402, 67, 'Vision, Mission & Strategic Direction', 'reading', '<p>Every organisation needs a clear sense of purpose. This lesson covers how to craft a compelling vision and mission that reflects both sound business principles and kingdom values. We examine how companies like TOMS, Grameen Bank and others have aligned profit with purpose, and what the church can learn from them.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 30, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1403, 67, 'Competitive Strategy in a Global Context', 'reading', '<p>Porter\'s Five Forces, Blue Ocean Strategy and other frameworks — viewed through the lens of Christian ethics. How do we compete without compromising character? How do we pursue excellence without succumbing to greed? This session equips you to think strategically while maintaining integrity.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 35, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1404, 67, 'Organisational Culture & Faith Integration', 'reading', '<p>Culture eats strategy for breakfast. This lesson explores how to build an organisational culture that embodies Christian values — trust, honesty, service, excellence — without alienating non-Christian stakeholders. Practical guidance on hiring, onboarding, performance management and team building.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 30, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1405, 67, 'Change Management & Innovation', 'reading', '<p>Leading change is one of the hardest tasks in business. Drawing on Kotter\'s 8-Step Model and biblical examples of change leadership (Nehemiah, Paul), this session provides a practical roadmap for guiding organisations through transformation with wisdom and compassion.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 30, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1406, 68, 'Understanding Financial Statements', 'reading', '<p>Every leader must read the numbers. This lesson demystifies the balance sheet, income statement and cash flow statement. You don\'t need to be an accountant, but you need to understand the financial story your organisation is telling. We walk through real financial statements and highlight the key indicators of financial health.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 35, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1407, 68, 'Budgeting & Financial Planning', 'reading', '<p>The budget is a moral document — it reveals what you truly value. This lesson covers zero-based budgeting, forecasting, variance analysis and how to align your financial plans with your strategic priorities. Special attention is given to budgeting in not-for-profit and ministry contexts.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 30, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1408, 68, 'Ethical Investment & Kingdom Capital', 'reading', '<p>Where do you put your money? This session explores faith-consistent investing, ethical banking, microfinance and innovative financing models for diaspora entrepreneurs. We examine the growing field of impact investing and how Christian leaders can deploy capital for both financial return and social/spiritual impact.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 35, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1409, 68, 'Risk Management & Financial Integrity', 'reading', '<p>Managing financial risk is a stewardship responsibility. From fraud prevention to insurance, from reserve policies to internal controls — this practical session equips leaders to protect their organisations and maintain the highest standards of financial integrity and transparency.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 30, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1410, 69, 'Marketing with Integrity', 'reading', '<p>Marketing is not manipulation. This session builds a theology and ethics of marketing — how we communicate value, build trust and serve customers honestly. From truth in advertising to pricing ethics, we explore how to market without compromising Christian witness.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 30, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1411, 69, 'Brand Strategy & Storytelling', 'reading', '<p>Your brand is your reputation. This lesson covers the fundamentals of brand strategy — positioning, differentiation, storytelling — through the lens of authenticity and purpose. Case studies include faith-led brands that have successfully communicated their values without being preachy.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 30, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1412, 69, 'Digital Marketing & Social Media Ethics', 'reading', '<p>The digital marketplace presents unprecedented opportunities and ethical pitfalls. From data privacy to algorithmic bias, from influencer culture to online community building, this session equips you to navigate digital marketing with wisdom and integrity.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 30, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1413, 69, 'Customer Service as Ministry', 'reading', '<p>Every customer interaction is an opportunity to reflect Christ\'s love. This lesson explores how exceptional customer service can be a form of witness, building loyalty and opening doors for meaningful conversations. Practical frameworks for handling complaints, serving diverse customers and creating a service culture.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 25, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1414, 70, 'Operations & Supply Chain Ethics', 'reading', '<p>How things get made and delivered matters to God. This lesson examines operations management — process design, quality control, logistics — through the lens of ethical supply chains, fair labour practices and environmental stewardship. Modern slavery in supply chains is a particular focus.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 30, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1415, 70, 'Entrepreneurship: From Idea to Venture', 'reading', '<p>Launching a new venture requires vision, resilience and practical know-how. This session covers business model generation, lean startup methodology, minimum viable products and fundraising. Special attention is given to the unique challenges and opportunities facing diaspora entrepreneurs.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 35, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1416, 70, 'Social Enterprise & the Common Good', 'reading', '<p>Social enterprises blend profit and purpose. This lesson explores different legal structures (CIC, B Corp, charity trading arms) and business models that prioritise social impact alongside financial sustainability. Case studies of successful faith-inspired social enterprises from around the world.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 30, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1417, 70, 'Business Planning & Pitching', 'reading', '<p>Every venture needs a plan. This practical session teaches you how to write a compelling business plan and pitch deck that communicates your vision, strategy and financial projections to investors, partners and stakeholders. We include a template and worked example.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 30, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1418, 71, 'Ethical Leadership in Practice', 'reading', '<p>Leadership is tested in moments of pressure. This session uses real-world case studies of ethical dilemmas — bribery, discrimination, environmental compromises — to develop your ethical decision-making muscles. We introduce several ethical frameworks (Virtue Ethics, the Four-Way Test, the Matthew 7 Principle) and apply them to complex scenarios.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 35, 1, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1419, 71, 'Corporate Governance & Board Leadership', 'reading', '<p>Good governance protects mission and ensures accountability. This lesson covers board structures, fiduciary duties, the role of non-executive directors and how to build governance frameworks that serve both commercial and missional objectives. Special attention to governance in family businesses and faith-based organisations.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 30, 2, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1420, 71, 'Leading for Impact: Measuring What Matters', 'reading', '<p>What gets measured gets done. This session explores the Balanced Scorecard, Triple Bottom Line (People, Planet, Profit) and Kingdom Impact frameworks for measuring organisational success beyond financial metrics. How do you track spiritual and social impact alongside commercial performance?</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 30, 3, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1421, 71, 'Capstone Integration: From Learning to Launch', 'reading', '<p>The MBA journey culminates in your capstone project. This final session guides you through integrating everything you have learned — theology, strategy, finance, marketing, operations and leadership — into a coherent, actionable business plan. Reflect on your personal leadership journey and prepare to launch your faith-led enterprise.</p><p>Work through the material at your own pace, reflect on the key ideas, and engage with your cohort in the discussion forum. Mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Integrate faith and business as a seamless whole, not separate domains.</li><li>Apply biblical principles of stewardship, justice and service to real business contexts.</li><li>Develop a global, diaspora-informed perspective on enterprise and ethics.</li></ul><blockquote>"Commit to the Lord whatever you do, and he will establish your plans." — Proverbs 16:3</blockquote>', NULL, 35, 4, NULL, NULL, NULL),
(1422, 72, 'Read: The Story of Scripture', 'reading', '<p>Read and reflect on the core material: The Story of Scripture.</p><p>This lesson combines a short reading with reflection questions. Work through the material at your own pace, then mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Ground every principle in Scripture and sound theology.</li><li>Apply learning to your own context and calling.</li><li>Engage critically with historical and contemporary perspectives.</li></ul><blockquote>"All Scripture is God-breathed and is useful for teaching, rebuking, correcting and training in righteousness." — 2 Timothy 3:16</blockquote>', NULL, 20, 11, NULL, 1, NULL),
(1423, 72, 'Study: The Story of Scripture', 'reading', '<p>Delve deeper into the key themes: The Story of Scripture.</p><p>This lesson combines a short reading with reflection questions. Work through the material at your own pace, then mark the lesson complete to unlock the next one.</p><h3>Key ideas</h3><ul><li>Ground every principle in Scripture and sound theology.</li><li>Apply learning to your own context and calling.</li><li>Engage critically with historical and contemporary perspectives.</li></ul><blockquote>"All Scripture is God-breathed and is useful for teaching, rebuking, correcting and training in righteousness." — 2 Timothy 3:16</blockquote>', NULL, 20, 12, NULL, 1, NULL),
